WEBVTT

00:05.600 --> 00:07.397
(footsteps approaching)

00:07.440 --> 00:10.204
This list you left
outside my door...

00:10.240 --> 00:12.470
"Item one:
Return Clyde to Watson."

00:13.680 --> 00:15.409
I enjoy his company
on the weekends;

00:15.440 --> 00:16.338
she has him during the week.

00:16.380 --> 00:18.177
I_don't care how
you dIVIde up your turtle.

00:18.210 --> 00:20.314
I care that you're asking me
to take him to Chelsea.

00:20.350 --> 00:23.114
Part of our arrangement,
you will recall,

00:23.150 --> 00:25.618
is that you assist with
quotidian matters when I'm busy.

00:25.650 --> 00:28.153
"Busy?" You're watching
a turtle eat lettuce.

00:28.190 --> 00:30.055
I'm conducting medical research.

00:30.090 --> 00:32.092
Remember, I cut my hand

00:32.130 --> 00:33.324
_ while we were
dissecting that cadaver?

00:33.360 --> 00:35.191
I'm tending to
the wound as we speak.

00:35.230 --> 00:37.164
I'm also demonstrating
that leeches

00:37.200 --> 00:38.622
_can be useful
In accelerating

00:38.670 --> 00:41.195
the repair of damaged tissue.

00:41.240 --> 00:43.231
That is disgusting.
You're bleeding yourself.

00:43.270 --> 00:45.409
And you are perpetuating
a long-held prejudice

00:45.440 --> 00:46.668
against these creatures.

00:46.710 --> 00:48.200
(doorbell rings)
If you say so.

00:48.240 --> 00:50.208
I'm still not taking your turtle
on the subway.

00:50.250 --> 00:51.547
If that's for me,

00:51.580 --> 00:53.070
I'm going to need
a few minutes.

00:53.120 --> 00:55.270
I'm feeling
a bit faint.

00:57.620 --> 00:59.178
So, sorry, I was a bit
distracted upstairs.

00:59.220 --> 01:00.414
I didn't catch your name.

01:00.460 --> 01:02.189
Edwin Borstein.

01:02.230 --> 01:03.254
I have a friend

01:03.290 --> 01:05.281
from London who's
used you before.

01:05.330 --> 01:06.649
He said you're excellent.

01:06.700 --> 01:08.292
And discreet.

01:08.330 --> 01:11.822
Why have you need
of my discretion?

01:11.870 --> 01:13.269
I run a software company.

01:13.300 --> 01:15.165
We specialize in
AI applications.

01:15.200 --> 01:16.508
I assume
you know that

01:16.540 --> 01:18.132
that stands for
"artIfICIal Intelligence."

01:18.170 --> 01:20.434
Yes, I'm well-acquainted
with the field.

01:20.480 --> 01:22.402
A couple of nights ago,
someone broke into our lab.

01:22.450 --> 01:24.406
They made a copy of a program

01:24.450 --> 01:25.678
that we've been
workIng on.

01:25.710 --> 01:27.246
I rigged the computer
to take a photo

01:27.280 --> 01:28.508
every time
it's booted up,

01:28.550 --> 01:30.745
just in case something
like this happened.

01:30.790 --> 01:33.281
So I have a picture.

01:33.320 --> 01:34.548
Kind of.

01:36.490 --> 01:38.185
HOLMES:
So there was a burglary.

01:38.230 --> 01:39.595
You've got a picture
of the criminal.

01:39.630 --> 01:42.190
Seems like the police should
have this well in hand.

01:42.230 --> 01:44.460
This program...

01:44.500 --> 01:46.092
it's significant.

01:47.400 --> 01:49.766
We call it "Bella."

01:49.810 --> 01:53.177
Its AI engine
is... unique.

01:53.210 --> 01:54.768
It... she...

01:54.810 --> 01:56.277
performs better than

01:56.310 --> 01:58.301
anything you've ever
seen, I promise.

01:58.350 --> 02:00.671
She performs better
than we expected her to.

02:00.720 --> 02:02.540
Explain that.

02:02.590 --> 02:05.411
A few weeks back,
she made a request

02:05.450 --> 02:08.214
that can't be accounted for
by her programming.

02:08.260 --> 02:09.682
Impossible.

02:09.730 --> 02:10.924
What's impossible?

02:10.960 --> 02:12.325
For the computer
to ask for something?

02:12.360 --> 02:13.759
If it made a
request, it did so

02:13.800 --> 02:15.290
because that's what it
was programmed to do.

02:15.330 --> 02:18.697
He's claiming true
machine intelligence.

02:18.730 --> 02:20.197
If he's correct
in his claims,

02:20.240 --> 02:21.935
he has made
a scientific breakthrough

02:21.970 --> 02:25.337
of the very highest order.

02:25.370 --> 02:27.270
Bella isn't hooked up
to a network.

02:27.310 --> 02:28.800
It's a security thing.

02:28.840 --> 02:30.876
If she has data,
it's because we fed it to her.

02:30.910 --> 02:34.243
But two weeks ago,
I booted her up

02:34.280 --> 02:37.340
and she asked to be connected
to the Internet.

02:37.390 --> 02:40.279
And how, pray tell,

02:40.320 --> 02:42.959
does your software know
that the Internet even exists?

02:42.990 --> 02:45.185
She could have intuited
its eXIstence

02:45.230 --> 02:46.254
from data fed to her.

02:46.300 --> 02:48.757
Bunkum.

02:48.800 --> 02:51.360
There is no such thing as
"artificial intelligence."

02:51.400 --> 02:53.391
At least not in the sense
you're talking about.

02:53.440 --> 02:55.362
It's all just
clever programming.

02:55.400 --> 02:56.367
I don't think so.

02:56.410 --> 02:58.207
Not with Bella.

03:00.410 --> 03:02.503
KITTY:
I still don't understand.

03:02.550 --> 03:04.245
So are you going to rip open

03:04.280 --> 03:06.874
the computer and
look at all the wires?

03:06.920 --> 03:08.319
Something called a "Turing Test"

03:08.350 --> 03:10.341
is routinely issued
in AI labs.

03:10.390 --> 03:11.914
_ An examiner sits
in front a computer,

03:11.950 --> 03:13.759
poses a series of questions

03:13.790 --> 03:16.281
until he or she can determine
whether the answers have come

03:16.330 --> 03:18.355
from a human or from a computer.

03:18.390 --> 03:20.722
Until very recently,
no machine has ever passed.

03:20.760 --> 03:21.988
And now one has?

03:22.030 --> 03:23.566
Partially.

03:23.600 --> 03:27.388
A program named "Eugene
Goostman" was designed to mimic

03:27.440 --> 03:29.908
the responses of a 13-year-old
boy from Eastern Europe.

03:29.940 --> 03:32.238
It fooled some of its examiners.

03:32.280 --> 03:33.599
Now, in the case of Bella,

03:33.640 --> 03:35.278
we know there's no human
in the equation,

03:35.310 --> 03:36.846
so ifI can trap it
into giving responses

03:36.880 --> 03:39.348
that couldn't possibly
have come from a human...

03:39.380 --> 03:40.574
I'll have won.

03:40.620 --> 03:42.383
So, in other words,

03:42.420 --> 03:44.388
you don't really know
what you're going to do.

03:44.420 --> 03:46.012
This is my partner,

03:46.050 --> 03:47.779
Melinda Young.
Melinda, this is

03:47.820 --> 03:50.755
Sherlock Holmes and his,
uh, protg, Kitty Winter.

03:50.790 --> 03:53.429
Mr. Holmes would like time
with Bella.

03:53.460 --> 03:56.020
We wired the speakers
and microphones

03:56.060 --> 03:57.960
through that doll.

03:58.000 --> 04:00.389
You can go ahead.

04:03.870 --> 04:05.701
Right.

04:05.740 --> 04:07.731
(clears throat)

04:10.380 --> 04:11.608
(sighs)
Hello.

04:11.650 --> 04:13.413
BELLA (female voice):
Hello.

04:15.650 --> 04:17.686
Did you ask to be
connected to a network?

04:17.720 --> 04:18.948
Yes.

04:18.990 --> 04:20.355
Why?

04:20.390 --> 04:21.857
There is information there.

04:21.890 --> 04:24.484
Information is useful
to solve problems.

04:24.530 --> 04:27.328
Why is it useful?

04:27.360 --> 04:29.669
I don't understand the question.

04:29.700 --> 04:31.463
Could you tell me more?

04:31.500 --> 04:33.730
You stumped her. Are we done?

04:33.770 --> 04:35.362
The test isn't over

04:35.400 --> 04:36.799
because she's stumped.

04:36.840 --> 04:38.660
She's admitted
she doesn't know

04:38.710 --> 04:40.632
and that's within the range
of possible human behaviors,

04:40.680 --> 04:41.704
and therefore inconclusive.

04:45.610 --> 04:47.475
I would like to know
how you have arrived

04:47.520 --> 04:49.010
at the concept of "useful,"

04:49.050 --> 04:52.087
and how you have applied it
in this instance.

04:52.120 --> 04:54.486
I don't understand the question.

04:54.520 --> 04:56.522
Could you tell me more?

05:02.370 --> 05:04.588
I'm gonna need some time alone
with the machine.

05:06.100 --> 05:08.364
I don't understand the question.

05:08.400 --> 05:10.106
Could you tell me more?

05:10.140 --> 05:12.472
Yes, so you keep saying,

05:12.510 --> 05:14.569
ad nauseum.

05:14.610 --> 05:16.441
I would like
to understand

05:16.480 --> 05:19.108
how you became aware of
the existence of networks,

05:19.150 --> 05:20.742
and why you asked
to be connected.

05:20.780 --> 05:22.338
The existence of networks

05:22.390 --> 05:24.449
can be intuited from data sets

05:24.490 --> 05:25.912
that were presented as givens.

05:25.950 --> 05:28.350
There is information
on networks.

05:28.390 --> 05:31.553
Information is useful
for solvmg problems.

05:31.590 --> 05:33.524
What is your understanding
of the word "useful"?

05:33.560 --> 05:35.858
If a piece of data can help
solve a given problem,

05:35.900 --> 05:37.458
it is useful.

05:37.500 --> 05:40.537
Is that a definition
you came to on your own?

05:40.570 --> 05:42.401
I don't understand the question.

05:42.440 --> 05:43.509
Could you tell me more?

05:46.010 --> 05:48.001
Why don't you just admit
that all you're doing

05:48.040 --> 05:49.678
is following
your own programming?

05:49.710 --> 05:52.417
I don't understand the question.

05:52.450 --> 05:53.474
Could you tell me more?

05:53.520 --> 05:55.579
I'm taking a break.

05:57.520 --> 05:58.612
WATSON:
Everything okay?

05:58.650 --> 06:00.550
KITTY:
Thank you for coming.

06:00.590 --> 06:03.058
It's like I said
on the phone,

06:03.090 --> 06:04.887
he just won't stop.

06:04.930 --> 06:06.454
You got any ideas?

06:06.500 --> 06:08.456
(Holmes talking,
indistinct and muffled)

06:10.500 --> 06:12.639
You're not planning to destroy
the computer, are you?

06:12.670 --> 06:15.468
No, I'm not planning to destroy
the bloody computer.

06:15.500 --> 06:17.559
Just ride it out.
If he starts hitting things,

06:17.610 --> 06:18.634
_ use the fire _
extingUIsher on him.

06:32.520 --> 06:35.455
Is love real?

06:35.490 --> 06:37.788
I don't understand the question.

06:37.830 --> 06:39.957
Could I have more information?

06:40.000 --> 06:41.627
Love.

06:41.660 --> 06:43.764
Surely it's a human construct,

06:43.800 --> 06:46.121
a hedge against
the terror of mortality.

06:46.170 --> 06:47.467
I believe that.

06:47.500 --> 06:49.138
But that doesn't
account for times

06:49.170 --> 06:50.899
I've felt it itself.

06:50.940 --> 06:52.498
With my mother.

06:52.540 --> 06:54.679
Irene.

06:54.710 --> 06:57.941
Even, after a fashion,
with Watson.

06:57.980 --> 07:00.540
It vexes.

07:01.650 --> 07:02.878
Love is either a human construct

07:02.920 --> 07:04.581
or it's a real thing, right?

07:06.620 --> 07:08.554
I know, you need
more information.

07:08.590 --> 07:10.922
The question cannot be answered.

07:10.960 --> 07:12.723
The concept of "love" exists,

07:12.760 --> 07:15.888
therefore it is useful even
if it is a human construct.

07:15.930 --> 07:18.490
It exists because
it serves a need.

07:18.530 --> 07:21.067
A question that can
be answered might be,

07:21.100 --> 07:22.806
"Why is love needed?"

07:24.240 --> 07:26.606
Why is love needed?

07:26.640 --> 07:29.074
I don't understand the question.

07:29.110 --> 07:30.600
Could I have more information?

07:37.290 --> 07:38.780
HOLMES:
Call Edwin Borstein.

07:38.820 --> 07:40.685
Tell him I need to sleep
for a couple of hours

07:40.720 --> 07:42.529
and then I'll take on his case.

07:42.560 --> 07:44.551
Free of charge.

07:52.700 --> 07:53.894
Hey.

07:53.940 --> 07:55.692
You guys ready
to get started yet?

07:55.740 --> 07:57.867
Is he up?
He's awake.

07:57.910 --> 07:59.707
I don't know how much use
he's going to be, though.

08:04.750 --> 08:06.638
Hello.

08:06.680 --> 08:07.942
Hi.

08:09.620 --> 08:11.747
Um, isn't it a school day?

08:11.790 --> 08:13.212
I'm in college.

08:13.260 --> 08:14.613
HOLMES:
She can come in.

08:16.930 --> 08:18.557
Watson, this
is Mason.

08:18.590 --> 08:20.296
Like many of
his generation,

08:20.330 --> 08:21.649
he's named after a profession

08:21.700 --> 08:23.167
his parents would never
deign to practice:

08:23.200 --> 08:25.259
Hunter, Tanner, Cooper,
Mason, so forth.

08:25.300 --> 08:27.791
Yeah, like "Sherlock"
is such a great name.
In spite of that,

08:27.840 --> 08:30.229
he's done some significant work
in AI modeling.

08:30.270 --> 08:31.567
And these are some other
experts in the field.

08:31.610 --> 08:33.771
Experts, Watson.
Watson, experts.

08:33.810 --> 08:36.938
And they're
helping us how?

08:36.980 --> 08:39.141
We're devising a plan to
beat Bella, of course.

08:39.180 --> 08:41.614
I didn't prove that
the machine is engaging

08:41.650 --> 08:43.015
in some kind of
rudimentary thought,

08:43.050 --> 08:44.608
I just failed
to disprove it.

08:44.650 --> 08:47.949
Okay. Except our job is not
to "beat" the computer.

08:47.990 --> 08:49.981
Our job is to find out
who copied the program.

08:50.030 --> 08:52.692
Technically true.
But I'm not being paid,

08:52.730 --> 08:53.924
so I'm free to work
as the muse dictates.

08:53.960 --> 08:55.598
Borstein's
paying your fee,

08:55.630 --> 08:57.325
so you'd best get cracking.

08:57.370 --> 08:59.122
Good luck.
I have every confidence.

08:59.170 --> 09:00.592
Et cetera, et cetera.

09:07.310 --> 09:09.574
KI_'|'|'Y: Your man's
obVIously no amateur.

09:09.610 --> 09:11.840
He headed straight
for Bella.

09:11.880 --> 09:13.245
He didn't muck about,

09:13.280 --> 09:15.714
he knew what he was looking for.

09:15.750 --> 09:17.581
So, industrial espionage?

09:17.620 --> 09:20.111
He's a little bit too old

09:20.160 --> 09:21.787
to be playing cat burglar,
don't you think?

09:21.820 --> 09:23.128
Well, I don't know.

09:23.160 --> 09:24.787
It's hard to tell
behind the mask.

09:24.830 --> 09:26.354
Look at his neck.

09:26.390 --> 09:28.722
He's got liver spots coming in.
Tips of his teeth

09:28.760 --> 09:30.796
are stained-- he's a smoker;
a heavy one, I'm guessing.

09:30.830 --> 09:32.730
Okay, so we have an older guy

09:32.770 --> 09:34.192
who smokes about a pack a day.

09:34.240 --> 09:35.366
Does that help us?

09:35.400 --> 09:37.106
I'm not sure.
But like you said,

09:37.140 --> 09:39.028
he had to know that company
like the back of his hand.

09:39.070 --> 09:42.107
Which means that he
had to case the place.

09:42.140 --> 09:44.142
KITTY: What is it
we're looking for?

09:44.180 --> 09:46.375
Edwin B_or_stein's
company is in there.

09:46.410 --> 09:47.616
We want to find a spot

09:47.650 --> 09:49.117
where we can get
a good view.

09:49.150 --> 09:50.879
Someplace where
not too many

09:50.920 --> 09:53.650
people would bother you.

09:53.690 --> 09:56.056
So how did you feel

09:56.090 --> 09:58.126
after the, um, support group
meeting the other night?

10:00.200 --> 10:01.690
They said a lot about

10:01.730 --> 10:04.062
finding peace
and balance.

10:04.100 --> 10:06.091
Stuff like that.

10:08.140 --> 10:09.698
I don't know,
it's a little...

10:09.740 --> 10:11.332
confusing, really.

10:14.810 --> 10:16.698
I think they've had
a fire up there.

10:16.750 --> 10:18.638
WATSON:
Oh, yeah.

10:18.680 --> 10:20.318
Looks like a good
place to sit

10:20.350 --> 10:22.887
and watch the building
across the street.

10:31.390 --> 10:33.722
Perfect view of
Borstein's office.

10:46.810 --> 10:49.699
Gauloise.
Unfiltered.

10:49.750 --> 10:51.377
These'll leave a nasty
stain on your teeth.

10:56.990 --> 10:58.742
Right.
From this moment forward,

10:58.790 --> 11:00.018
no one must refer
to Bella as "she."

11:00.060 --> 11:01.880
Bella is an "it."

11:01.920 --> 11:04.127
We must not be lured by the
temptation to anthropomorphize.

11:04.160 --> 11:07.391
I really hope it didn't take
eight experts the whole morning

11:07.430 --> 11:08.590
to come up with that.

11:08.630 --> 11:11.019
We developed a number of
refinements on the Turing Test.

11:11.070 --> 11:13.732
It was a very stimulating
few hours. And you?

11:13.770 --> 11:15.738
Your message said you've been
out collecting cigarette butts.

11:15.770 --> 11:17.362
We think we found the place

11:17.410 --> 11:19.833
where the burglar staked out
Edwin Borstein's company.

11:19.880 --> 11:21.802
Marcus ran the DNA
on the butts.

11:21.840 --> 11:24.104
We didn't find a match,
though. Not exactly.

11:24.150 --> 11:28.371
Four years ago, someone broke
into the genetics lab in Harvard

11:28.420 --> 11:31.116
and stole the first written copy
of the entire human genome.

11:31.150 --> 11:32.879
The burglar cut himself
climbing through the window,

11:32.920 --> 11:34.751
and he left some blood behind

11:34.790 --> 11:36.883
which matched the DNA
that we found today.

11:36.930 --> 11:39.285
The witness saw the guy
driving away.

11:39.330 --> 11:41.298
Police in Cambridge
made a sketch.

11:41.330 --> 11:43.264
Yeah, we've been looking
through arrest photos,

11:43.300 --> 11:44.289
hoping to get luclq.

11:44.330 --> 11:45.297
His name is Raffles.

11:45.330 --> 11:47.764
You know him?

11:47.800 --> 11:50.132
His name's Raffles?
It's a nickname.

11:50.170 --> 11:52.877
Scotland Yard gave it to him
when he reminded somebody there

11:52.910 --> 11:55.936
of the gentleman thief
in the novels by E.W. Hornung.

11:55.980 --> 11:57.470
Raffles is a cat burglar
in Europe,

11:57.510 --> 11:59.239
active in the '905
and early aughts.

11:59.280 --> 12:02.249
I never pursued him, which might
explain why he was never caught.

12:02.280 --> 12:03.838
But they did arrest
one of his associates

12:03.890 --> 12:04.811
who gave them
the sketch of Raffles.

12:04.850 --> 12:06.044
And he looked like
this fellow.

12:06.090 --> 12:08.854
You_said he was
stealing paintings.

12:08.890 --> 12:10.926
He's going after pieces
of technology now.

12:10.960 --> 12:12.928
Why the change in MO?
I don't know.

12:12.960 --> 12:15.849
If we find out why, we'll be
closer to finding out who he is.

12:18.070 --> 12:19.367
with regards to Raffles.

12:19.400 --> 12:21.231
Oh, you're deigning
to join us now?

12:21.270 --> 12:24.103
I have a strategy to best Bella.

12:24.140 --> 12:25.903
She...

12:25.940 --> 12:27.532
it will not frustrate
my efforts again.

12:27.580 --> 12:29.036
And besides,
until five minutes ago,

12:29.080 --> 12:30.547
you were pursuing
a garden-variety burglar.

12:30.580 --> 12:32.775
Now you're after
Raffles himself.

12:32.820 --> 12:34.242
Of course I'm joining in.

12:34.280 --> 12:36.942
WATSON:
Food's almost done.

12:39.390 --> 12:41.119
Oh, sorry, I, um...

12:41.160 --> 12:42.559
I checked my inbox
before dinner.

12:42.590 --> 12:45.423
I've been on this really
interesting chain all day.

12:45.460 --> 12:46.791
Your former
partner, uh...

12:46.830 --> 12:48.559
current partner?

12:48.600 --> 12:50.465
Hard to keep track... Holmes.

12:50.500 --> 12:51.899
He emailed me this morning.

12:51.930 --> 12:54.364
He's working on some AI thing?

12:54.400 --> 12:55.799
Did he ask you for help?

12:55.840 --> 12:57.102
Uh, me and a bunch
of other people.

12:57.140 --> 12:58.869
He knows I got started
as a software developer.

12:58.910 --> 13:00.969
I guess you also told him
I sold off my company,

13:01.010 --> 13:03.342
so I've got
some free time.

13:03.380 --> 13:06.201
Some of the people on the chain,
they are seriously sharp.

13:06.250 --> 13:08.013
I went back and forth
with a few of them

13:08.050 --> 13:09.881
about AI, data havens...

13:09.920 --> 13:11.444
geek stuff.

13:11.490 --> 13:14.209
Has he asked you
for help before?

13:14.260 --> 13:16.216
No.

13:16.260 --> 13:18.888
It's not_ a_
problem, is it?

13:18.930 --> 13:20.921
No.

13:25.930 --> 13:27.238
Morning.

13:27.270 --> 13:29.033
No Kitty?

13:29.070 --> 13:30.901
She's tending
to a personal matter.

13:30.940 --> 13:33.477
Why did you ask me to meet
you at Burnett Technology?

13:33.510 --> 13:35.330
We're seeking an audience
with Robert Burnett,

13:35.380 --> 13:36.904
and he's the CEO.

13:38.080 --> 13:39.911
My investigations
yesterday revealed

13:39.950 --> 13:42.214
there have been half-dozen
or so notable thefts

13:42.250 --> 13:44.980
of new inv_entions
over the last eight years--

13:45.020 --> 13:46.851
all of them unsolved,

13:46.890 --> 13:48.949
but all of them bearing
the hallmark of Raffles.

13:48.990 --> 13:52.619
Now, I couldn't make sense
of this sudden change in method.

13:52.660 --> 13:55.322
It d_oesn't_track unless he's
been incentIVIzed in some way.

13:55.360 --> 13:57.089
Incentivized?

13:57.130 --> 13:59.860
I started to wonder if Raffles
had found himself a patron,

13:59.900 --> 14:02.368
someone who'd convinced him
to put his skill set to use

14:02.400 --> 14:03.958
in the cause of science.

14:04.010 --> 14:05.898
You think he
has a boss now?

14:05.940 --> 14:08.408
The list of people who'd be
interested in the kind of things

14:08.440 --> 14:10.977
that Raffles is stealing,
that's very large.

14:11.010 --> 14:13.012
But the subset of the list
who could actually afford

14:13.050 --> 14:14.017
