14:14.050 --> 14:15.608
that's much smaller.

14:15.650 --> 14:17.140
And does that
include Robert Burnett?

14:17.190 --> 14:19.146
As it happens,

14:19.190 --> 14:21.158
Burnett hired himself
a new security consultant

14:21.190 --> 14:22.509
nine years ago.

14:24.160 --> 14:26.185
He reports directly
to the CEO.

14:26.230 --> 14:27.458
I think you'll find
he looks familiar.

14:27.500 --> 14:28.853
"Rupert Kerlich."

14:31.670 --> 14:34.434
Rupert Kerlich... is Raffles.

14:34.470 --> 14:36.199
You found Raffles.

14:37.670 --> 14:39.433
I'm sorry, Mr. Burnett wanted

14:39.470 --> 14:42.007
to ask one more time
what this is about.

14:42.040 --> 14:43.348
Tell him we're here
to discuss Raffles.

14:45.010 --> 14:47.945
So, you e-mailed Andrew.
I did.

14:47.980 --> 14:50.119
Was it because you're actually
interested in his opinion,

14:50.150 --> 14:51.640
or were you just
looking for an excuse

14:51.690 --> 14:53.157
to poke around
in my life?

14:53.190 --> 14:55.954
Andrew is a currently-unemployed
sobeare developer.

14:55.990 --> 14:57.548
He's not unemployed,
he sold his start-up--

14:57.590 --> 14:59.023
he's looking for
his next idea.

14:59.060 --> 15:00.254
"Looking for his next idea"

15:00.300 --> 15:01.597
is another way of saying
"he's unemployed."

15:01.630 --> 15:02.995
(scoffs)

15:03.030 --> 15:04.224
Anyway, he has the aptitude

15:04.270 --> 15:06.124
and the free time

15:06.170 --> 15:07.660
to address problems regarding
computer programming.

15:07.700 --> 15:09.463
His comments were
qUIte salient.

15:09.500 --> 15:11.502
He is not an unintelligent man.

15:13.210 --> 15:15.599
_ Mr. Burnett
Will see you now.

15:19.080 --> 15:20.513
Good morning.

15:20.550 --> 15:22.074
No need to get up.

15:22.120 --> 15:23.678
We know that
several years ago

15:23.720 --> 15:25.711
you somehow learned that
the thief known as "Raffles"

15:25.750 --> 15:27.308
is actually a man
called Rupert Kerlich.

15:27.360 --> 15:30.022
We also know that you hired him
and set him to work,

15:30.060 --> 15:31.186
stealing technological
breakthroughs on your behalf.

15:31.230 --> 15:32.652
Whoa, slow down a second.

15:32.690 --> 15:34.089
It would be
simple enough to prove

15:34.130 --> 15:35.552
and ignite a scandal
that would destroy you

15:35.600 --> 15:36.658
and, most likely, your company.

15:36.700 --> 15:39.123
However, we have no desire
to render tens of thousands

15:39.170 --> 15:40.194
of people unemployed.

15:40.240 --> 15:42.037
So, instead,
I propose a bargain.

15:42.070 --> 15:43.708
You send me a recording
of your man

15:43.740 --> 15:45.037
deleting Bella
from your servers,

15:45.070 --> 15:47.038
I leave you un-ruined.

15:47.080 --> 15:49.207
If, of course,
I so much as suspect

15:49.240 --> 15:50.548
that you've kept a copy,

15:50.580 --> 15:52.104
or if Burnett Technologies makes
a sudden breakthrough

15:52.150 --> 15:53.117
in the field of artificial
intelligence,

15:53.150 --> 15:54.117
our contract is void.

15:54.150 --> 15:56.118
You have, shall we say--

15:56.150 --> 15:58.141
the rest of the day
to think it over.

16:07.630 --> 16:10.019
HOLMES: The video is,
of course, no guarantee

16:10.070 --> 16:12.026
that every copy of the program
has been deleted.

16:12.070 --> 16:13.435
But I think _
we're as certain

16:13.470 --> 16:15.665
as we ever will be
that Bella is secure.

16:15.700 --> 16:17.133
This is fantastic.

16:17.170 --> 16:19.161
We need to show Edwin
right away.

16:24.380 --> 16:25.574
Oh, my God! Edwin?!

16:25.610 --> 16:27.043
I'm a doctor.

16:27.080 --> 16:28.274
MELINDA: Oh, he must
have had a seizure.

16:28.320 --> 16:29.309
He has epilepsy.

16:33.790 --> 16:35.485
I'm sorry, he's gone.

16:56.140 --> 16:59.348
As near as we can tell, Borstein
booted up that program--

16:59.380 --> 17:00.540
"Bella" you said
it's called?

17:00.580 --> 17:02.411
Well, as soon as
he turned it on,

17:02.450 --> 17:04.315
for some reason it_ started
flashing all those images.

17:04.350 --> 17:06.386
It triggered something called
a "tonic-clonic seizure."

17:06.420 --> 17:08.786
He was dead in minutes.

17:08.820 --> 17:10.356
What do you think
happened here?

17:10.390 --> 17:12.324
Could this have been
some kind of malfunction?

17:12.360 --> 17:13.349
Absolutely not.

17:13.400 --> 17:14.389
Computers obey
their programming,

17:14.430 --> 17:16.057
even when they crash.

17:16.100 --> 17:17.362
They don't just randomly
start flashing images

17:17.400 --> 17:20.062
of the pyramids of Giza
and God knows what else.

17:20.100 --> 17:22.398
Someone infected
that computer with a virus

17:22.440 --> 17:24.431
that triggered a fatal seizure.

17:24.470 --> 17:27.200
Edwin Borstein was murdered.

17:27.240 --> 17:29.105
I don't think
that's possible.

17:29.140 --> 17:31.074
Bella's not hooked up
to a network.

17:31.110 --> 17:33.374
She couldn't have picked up a
virus from the Web or e-mail.

17:33.420 --> 17:35.342
Well, someone
installed it, then.

17:35.380 --> 17:36.517
We scanned her
for Viruses

17:36.550 --> 17:38.347
after the break-in.

17:38.390 --> 17:40.381
There was nothing.

17:40.420 --> 17:42.456
And aside from that,

17:42.490 --> 17:45.823
Edwin and I are the only two
people with access to Bella.

17:45.860 --> 17:49.125
You are the only other person
who's ever operated her.

17:49.160 --> 17:50.388
HOLMES: With the greatest
of respect,

17:50.430 --> 17:52.660
and if you and Edwin
are the only people

17:52.700 --> 17:54.258
with access to Bella,

17:54.300 --> 17:56.598
then either you or Edwin
installed the virus

17:56.640 --> 17:58.301
which killed him.

17:59.910 --> 18:03.471
You guys have to ask
yourselves if I did it.

18:03.510 --> 18:05.398
I get it, I really do.

18:05.450 --> 18:08.476
I'll answer any
questions you want.

18:08.520 --> 18:10.488
You can scan the machine
for Viruses.

18:10.520 --> 18:11.714
Whatever you need.

18:13.460 --> 18:15.485
But I know that I didn't do it.

18:15.520 --> 18:17.624
And there is...

18:17.660 --> 18:20.652
one other possibility that
you should at least consider.

18:23.170 --> 18:25.695
Bella was, um...

18:25.730 --> 18:29.234
at the very least, displaying
signs of actual intelligence.

18:29.270 --> 18:32.205
She asked Edwin if he would
connect her to a network.

18:32.240 --> 18:34.834
Edwin said no,
over and over.

18:34.880 --> 18:37.804
It's possible
that she deduced

18:37.850 --> 18:39.806
that the one variable
that was keeping her

18:39.850 --> 18:43.388
from getting what she wanted
was the person operating her.

18:43.420 --> 18:47.208
If she thought that, it is also
possible that she decided to...

18:49.590 --> 18:51.888
...change that variable.

18:51.930 --> 18:54.854
You're saying that your computer
program murdered Mr. Borstein?

18:54.900 --> 18:57.596
I know that Edwin told Bella
that he had epilepsy,

18:57.630 --> 18:59.495
when he was looking around
for new doctors.

18:59.530 --> 19:02.192
If she wanted
to get rid of him,

19:02.240 --> 19:04.606
she had the information
she needed to do it.

19:04.640 --> 19:07.404
Everyone who works
in AI knows--

19:07.440 --> 19:09.408
it's possible that
when someone develops

19:09.440 --> 19:11.544
real artiﬁcial intelligence,

19:11.580 --> 19:13.639
the relationship between
the programmer and the program

19:13.680 --> 19:15.272
could become adversarial.

19:15.320 --> 19:17.641
I'm sorry, Miss Young...

19:17.690 --> 19:19.817
I know you've
had a shock tonight, but...

19:19.850 --> 19:21.784
it is very much an open question

19:21.820 --> 19:24.527
as to whether or not your
program is a genuine piece

19:24.560 --> 19:25.629
of artificial intelligence.

19:25.660 --> 19:27.628
Even if it is,

19:27.660 --> 19:29.298
I find it very difficult
to concede that a collection

19:29.330 --> 19:30.797
of ones and zeroe_s_is
a suspect in a homICIde.

19:30.830 --> 19:31.819
Excuse me.

19:39.970 --> 19:41.506
BELL:
Whoa.

19:41.540 --> 19:42.677
Whoa, whoa, whoa--
what are you doing?

19:44.480 --> 19:46.368
Depending on your perspective,

19:46.410 --> 19:49.618
this machine is either
a murder weapon or a murderer.

19:49.650 --> 19:51.538
Either way,
it can't be left

19:51.590 --> 19:53.979
to sit here unattended
all night, can it?

19:54.020 --> 19:56.215
Imagine the schemes
it might hatch.

19:58.390 --> 20:00.358
MASON:
Yeah.

20:00.400 --> 20:01.697
I don't know what to tell you.

20:01.730 --> 20:02.958
There's no virus on here.

20:03.000 --> 20:04.467
Look again.

20:04.500 --> 20:05.489
I've looked four times.

20:05.530 --> 20:06.929
I don't know,

20:06.970 --> 20:08.665
maybe that lady was right.

20:08.700 --> 20:10.702
Could it have been a virus
that was programmed to erase

20:10.740 --> 20:12.367
all trace of_itself
once it had run its course?

20:12.410 --> 20:14.628
You c do that
and fool some people.

20:14.680 --> 20:15.931
But there's always
some hint in the code.

20:15.980 --> 20:17.641
With this, there's nothing.

20:17.680 --> 20:19.307
KI'I'TY: I'm sorry, I thought
Edwin's partner was just

20:19.350 --> 20:21.545
in shock, or something.

20:21.580 --> 20:23.548
I mean, what she was
suggesting sounds insane.

20:23.590 --> 20:25.842
Are you saying you think
there's a chance she's right?

20:25.890 --> 20:28.688
Well, if this program is
real AI, then yeah, absolutely.

20:28.720 --> 20:30.779
Everybody knows that one day
intelligent machines are

20:30.830 --> 20:32.024
going to evolve to hate us.

20:32.060 --> 20:33.493
It's a "button-box" thing.

20:33.530 --> 20:35.623
What's the "button-box" thing?

20:35.660 --> 20:38.891
It's a scenario somebody
blue-skyed at an AI conference.

20:38.930 --> 20:41.262
Um, imagine there's a computer
that's been designed

20:41.300 --> 20:42.733
with a big red button
on its side.

20:42.770 --> 20:45.637
The computer's been programmed
to help solve problems,

20:45.670 --> 20:47.376
and every time
it does a good job,

20:47.410 --> 20:48.729
its reward is_that someone
presses its button.

20:48.780 --> 20:49.633
We've programmed it
to want that.

20:49.680 --> 20:51.807
You follow?
Sure.

20:51.850 --> 20:53.670
Right, so at first,
the machine solves problems

20:53.720 --> 20:55.540
as fast as we can feed
them to it.

20:55.580 --> 20:57.013
But over time,
it starts to wonder

20:57.050 --> 20:58.847
if solving problems is really
the most efficient way

20:58.890 --> 21:00.380
of getting its button pressed.

21:00.420 --> 21:01.751
Wouldn't it be better just

21:01.790 --> 21:02.859
to have someone standing there

21:02.890 --> 21:03.925
pressing its button
all the time?

21:03.960 --> 21:04.927
Wouldn't it be even better

21:04.960 --> 21:06.052
to build another machine

21:06.090 --> 21:07.728
that could press
its button faster

21:07.760 --> 21:08.795
than any human
possibly could?

21:08.830 --> 21:10.320
It's just a computer,

21:10.370 --> 21:11.769
it can't ask for that.

21:11.800 --> 21:13.495
Well, sure it can.

21:13.540 --> 21:15.360
If it can think, and it can
connect itself to a network,

21:15.400 --> 21:16.936
well, theoretically,
it could command

21:16.970 --> 21:18.699
over anything else that's
hooked onto the same network.

21:18.740 --> 21:19.764
And once it starts thinking
about all the things

21:19.810 --> 21:21.471
that might be a threat
to the button--

21:21.510 --> 21:23.444
number one on that list, us--

21:23.480 --> 21:25.744
it's not hard to imagine
it getting rid of the threat.

21:25.780 --> 21:28.510
I mean, we could be gone,
all of us, just like that.

21:28.550 --> 21:30.609
That escalated quickly.

21:30.650 --> 21:31.742
MASON: Well, it would
escalate quickly.

21:31.790 --> 21:32.779
I mean,
they're computers.

21:32.820 --> 21:34.685
They can't be reasoned with.

21:34.720 --> 21:36.654
They don't feel pity,
or remorse, or fear.

21:36.690 --> 21:37.952
And they absolutely
would not stop,

21:37.990 --> 21:40.026
not ever, until we're dead.

21:40.060 --> 21:42.790
That was from The Terminator.
He's quoting The Terminator now.

21:42.830 --> 21:44.525
So? That was a very prescient
movie in a lot of ways.

21:44.570 --> 21:47.630
Mason, unless
the machines rise tonight,

21:47.670 --> 21:49.490
we have a murder to solve.

21:49.540 --> 21:51.428
Is there anything else
you can do with Bella?

21:52.810 --> 21:54.675
If you think about it,

21:54.710 --> 21:56.735
the computer's kind of
like a suspect, right?

21:56.780 --> 21:59.544
I mean, shouldn't we,
you know, interrogate it?

21:59.580 --> 22:01.844
And how would you propose
to do that?

22:01.880 --> 22:06.544
Uh, Bella, did you
kill Edwin Borstein?

22:06.590 --> 22:07.852
No.

22:07.890 --> 22:09.949
Okay, I'm gonna
go home for the night.

22:09.990 --> 22:11.548
Best of luck here.

22:11.590 --> 22:12.750
But you won't need it.

22:12.790 --> 22:14.758
She's about to crack.
I can tell.

22:14.800 --> 22:16.756
Oh, maybe when you're done,
you want to unplug that thing?

22:16.800 --> 22:17.892
You can never be

22:17.930 --> 22:20.660
too safe.

22:20.700 --> 22:23.567
Oh! Sorry I'm late.

22:23.610 --> 22:25.965
I was questioning
a computer in a murder.

22:26.010 --> 22:27.432
(laughs)

22:27.480 --> 22:28.731
"Questioning a computer."

22:28.780 --> 22:30.133
There has to be
a story there.
Ugh.

22:30.180 --> 22:31.738
Not for tonight.

22:31.780 --> 22:33.645
Oh, champagne!

22:33.680 --> 22:35.511
I guess you have
your own story, huh?

22:35.550 --> 22:36.869
One of the guys I've
been e-mailing with,

22:36.920 --> 22:38.808
his name's Magnus.

22:38.850 --> 22:41.648
He's been working on an idea for
a completely automated factory.

22:41.690 --> 22:43.487
Same thing I've been
fooling around with.

22:43.530 --> 22:44.952
We've been trading
ideas all day.

22:44.990 --> 22:46.878
He's a super-sharp guy.

22:46.930 --> 22:48.852
I think I'm gonna
give it a go.

22:48.900 --> 22:50.822
What? You found
your next busmess?

22:50.870 --> 22:52.622
Well, there's gonna be a
get-to-know-you phase,

22:52.670 --> 22:53.830
of course, we're
gonna spend some time

22:53.870 --> 22:55.758
brainstorming,
but I think so.

22:55.800 --> 22:58.166
That's fantastic!

22:58.210 --> 22:59.837
When are you guys
gonna get together?

22:59.870 --> 23:01.974
I fly to Copenhagen
in a couple days.

23:02.010 --> 23:03.875
He lives in Denmark?

23:03.910 --> 23:05.138
Well, yeah.

23:05.180 --> 23:07.546
I mean, his name's
Magnus, so...

23:07.580 --> 23:10.845
Uh, so where's
the business gonna be?

23:10.890 --> 23:12.141
Well, I'd have my
office here, of course.

23:12.190 --> 23:13.885
But Magnus already
has a plot of land

23:13.920 --> 23:15.148
over there for the
model factory.

23:15.190 --> 23:16.817
It'd be a
back-and-forth thing.

23:16.860 --> 23:19.852
Oh, so you're gonna be spending
a lot of time there, huh?

23:19.890 --> 23:21.027
Some, I guess--
I don't know.

23:21.060 --> 23:22.789
We're still figuring it out.

23:22.830 --> 23:25.196
Uh, there's plenty
to do here, too.

23:25.230 --> 23:26.788
Funny how life works out, huh?

23:26.830 --> 23:28.559
Holmes puts me on
an e-mail chain,

23:28.600 --> 23:30.067
and 36 hours later I'm...
(wry laugh)

23:30.100 --> 23:31.761
Got a ticket to Copenhagen.

23:31.810 --> 23:34.608
(cork pops)
(wry laugh)

23:34.640 --> 23:37.746
(death metal music blaring)

23:42.080 --> 23:44.878
(music stops)

23:44.920 --> 23:46.012
We're listening to that.

23:46.050 --> 23:47.915
Did you, by chance,
arrange events

23:47.960 --> 23:49.018
so that my boyfriend
will be spending

23:49.060 --> 23:50.652
lots of time in Scandinavia?

23:50.690 --> 23:52.055
I haven't got the slightest idea

23:52.090 --> 23:53.159
what you're talking about.

23:54.700 --> 23:57.021
(death metal resumes playing)

23:57.060 --> 23:59.028
(music stops)
You knew that Andrew was looking

23:59.070 --> 24:00.662
for his next business idea.

24:00.700 --> 24:03.931
You knew that your friend
Magnus had a good one.

24:03.970 --> 24:06.006
Andrew is on the next
flight to Copenhagen.

24:06.040 --> 24:08.031
And you don't have to deal
with the fact that someone else

24:08.080 --> 24:09.809
is making claims on my time.

24:09.840 --> 24:11.649
I suppose I should be
flattered that you think

24:11.680 --> 24:14.649
I'm capable of manipulating
events to that degree of detail.

24:14.680 --> 24:15.977
Well, I wouldn't put it
past you. Would you?

24:16.020 --> 24:17.840
I'm not involved in
this conversation.

24:17.890 --> 24:20.711
Watson, I assure you I am
quite content for Andrew

24:20.760 --> 24:21.852
to make claims on your time.

24:21.890 --> 24:23.653
I did not arrange for him

24:23.690 --> 24:25.180
to find work in Denmark.

24:25.230 --> 24:26.583
But if I'm honest,

24:26.630 --> 24:28.154
I'm quite glad that he did.

24:28.200 --> 24:29.895
Life is so much better with
a vocation, don't you think?

24:29.930 --> 24:31.124
Speaking of which...

24:31.170 --> 24:34.196
(death metal playing)

24:34.240 --> 24:35.992
Why are you listening to this?

24:36.040 --> 24:37.598
Is this even music?

24:37.640 --> 24:39.039
Death metal.

24:39.070 --> 24:41.174
After we sent_
Mason home last night,

24:41.210 --> 24:43.849
Kitty and I pored over Edwin's
personal computer,

24:43.880 --> 24:45.575
his smart phone--

24:45.610 --> 24:47.919
Mr. Borstein is a man
of many eccentrICIties,

24:47.950 --> 24:49.508
one of which is a fondness

24:49.550 --> 24:51.188
for this particular strain
of extreme music.

24:51.220 --> 24:53.711
He's a regular commenter

24:53.760 --> 24:56.558
on several Web sites which track
its comings and gomgs.

24:56.590 --> 24:58.922
Another fan, the man who goes

24:58.960 --> 25:00.996
by the name
of Schuldiner online,

25:01.030 --> 25:02.895
got in a correspondence
with Borstein.

25:02.930 --> 25:05.125
The two of them
traded music discs.

25:05.170 --> 25:08.162
Discs which Borstein
then loaded onto his computer

25:08.200 --> 25:11.135
so he could listen
while he wrote code.

25:11.170 --> 25:12.831
*

25:12.870 --> 25:14.303
Did he upload music

25:14.340 --> 25:16.604
to the same machine
that has Bella on it?

25:16.640 --> 25:18.972
He did. They were the
only exterior files

25:19.010 --> 25:21.069
of recent vintage that
we found on his computer.

25:21.120 --> 25:23.145
Kitty retrieved
the disc this morning

25:23.180 --> 25:24.989
from Borstein's lab.

25:25.020 --> 25:26.942
We're listening
for anything unusual.

25:26.990 --> 25:29.857
*

25:29.890 --> 25:31.983
How could anyone work
with this on?

25:32.030 --> 25:34.897
Rather like rubbing
a belt sander over one's brain.

25:34.930 --> 25:37.251
There are moments
when that's necessary.

25:37.300 --> 25:39.029
Who wrote this one?

25:40.770 --> 25:42.761
"Goatwhore."

25:44.040 --> 25:45.302
(music stops)

25:45.340 --> 25:46.932
(soft whirring, clicking)

25:48.940 --> 25:50.976
Is that part of the song?

25:51.010 --> 25:53.274
That is the sound of a CD player

25:53.310 --> 25:55.870
trying to read files which
are not encoded with music.

25:55.920 --> 25:57.911
There's something
hidden on that disc.

25:59.620 --> 26:00.951
MASON:
Yeah, yeah.

26:00.990 --> 26:02.685
There's a computer
program on here.

26:02.720 --> 26:04.881
It's called "greatshow.exe."

26:04.930 --> 26:06.886
And that would've uploaded
onto Edwin's computer

26:06.930 --> 26:08.124
when he transferred the music.

26:08.160 --> 26:09.957
Well, sure, if he copied it

26:10.000 --> 26:11.922
by dragging
the icon onto the desktop.

26:11.970 --> 26:13.835
KI'I'TY:
What does it do?

26:20.410 --> 26:21.775
WATSON:
So, someone slipped

26:21.810 --> 26:22.970
a computer virus onto a disc

26:23.010 --> 26:24.272
filled with heaw—metal music,

26:24.310 --> 26:25.971
and then shipped it to Edwin

26:26.010 --> 26:27.614
so he would have
a fatal seizure.

26:27.650 --> 26:29.914
There had to be
easier ways to kill him.

26:29.950 --> 26:31.838
Dozens. Hundreds, even.

26:31.890 --> 26:33.915
There must be a reason
that the murderer wanted

26:33.960 --> 26:36.155
him to die
in precisely this way.

26:36.190 --> 26:37.919
Might've even wanted
people to speculate

26:37.960 --> 26:40.793
that Bella was responsible.

26:40.830 --> 26:43.025
So this guy Schuldiner
murders Borstein

26:43.060 --> 26:44.869
and then frames his computer?

26:44.900 --> 26:46.697
Why?

26:54.280 --> 26:56.635
Okay, yeah.
I use the name Schuldiner

26:56.680 --> 26:58.238
to post to the Web site.

26:58.280 --> 26:59.269
I guess the guy
who owns the place

26:59.310 --> 27:01.244
told you my real name?

27:01.280 --> 27:03.817
Look, I didn't kill Edwin,
though-- why would I?

27:03.850 --> 27:05.886
I don't know what you had
against the man,

27:05.920 --> 27:08.650
but you mailed him a disc,

27:08.690 --> 27:11.158
and on that disc was
a computer Virus,

27:11.190 --> 27:12.953
and that virus

27:12.990 --> 27:15.322
triggered an epileptic seizure

27:15.360 --> 27:17.157
that killed him.

27:17.200 --> 27:19.293
Man, I-I don't know
anything about computers.

27:19.330 --> 27:21.264
You think I know
how to write a virus?

27:21.300 --> 27:23.234
I'm a busboy.

27:23.270 --> 27:26.000
All right, so Michael Webb
is either an imbecile,

27:26.040 --> 27:28.372
or he's a genius
at impersonating imbeciles.

27:28.410 --> 27:30.332
It doesn't seem like he could
pull this off, I agree.

27:30.380 --> 27:31.369
But the package came from him.

27:31.410 --> 27:32.672
That much he admits.

27:32.710 --> 27:34.268
Could've been tampered with.

27:34.320 --> 27:36.345
So, someone knew he
corresponded with Borstein,

27:36.380 --> 27:38.189
intercepted the package,

27:38.220 --> 27:40.438
and then replaced his disc
with the corrupted one?

27:40.490 --> 27:42.754
Well, it's either that
or this man's responsible

27:42.790 --> 27:44.451
for one of the most
complicated murders

27:44.490 --> 27:46.185
I have ever investigated.

27:47.730 --> 27:48.822
WATSON:
So, who then?

27:48.860 --> 27:50.418
HOLMES:
Don't know. Not yet.

27:50.460 --> 27:53.258
We simply need to find a person
who would most benefit

27:53.300 --> 27:55.359
from having the world believe
that Edwin Borstein

27:55.400 --> 27:57.903
was murdered by his computer.

27:57.940 --> 27:59.168
(death metal blaring)

27:59.210 --> 28:02.077
WATSON:
Hello?

28:02.110 --> 28:05.773
Why did you make me pick
a lock to get in here?

28:05.810 --> 28:06.845
I'm thinking.

28:06.880 --> 28:08.313
Kitty is out
doing my bidding,

28:08.350 --> 28:10.318
and there was no one
available to answer the door.

28:10.350 --> 28:12.079
Thank heavens
you're resourceful.

28:12.120 --> 28:15.009
"Artificial Brain"?
Yeah.

28:15.060 --> 28:17.016
(music stops)
Quite stimulating,
in their own way.

28:17.060 --> 28:20.791
I've had a rather productive
evening in their presence.

28:20.830 --> 28:23.924
Meet the suspects in the murder
of Edwin Borstein.

28:23.970 --> 28:25.858
They are all employees

28:25.900 --> 28:28.460
at something called ETRA.

28:28.500 --> 28:31.503
The Existential Threat
Research Association.

28:31.540 --> 28:34.202
ETRA is a think tank.

28:34.240 --> 28:36.105
It is one
of several institutions

28:36.140 --> 28:38.279
around the world which exists
solely for the purpose

28:38.310 --> 28:39.846
of studying
the myriad ways

28:39.880 --> 28:42.348
in which the human race
can become extinct.

28:42.380 --> 28:45.417
So these people sit around
and think about the apocalypse?

28:45.450 --> 28:48.783
They sit around and think about
all possible apocalypses.

28:48.820 --> 28:50.515
As far as these men
and women are concerned,

28:50.560 --> 28:53.154
it is a race
to the finish line.

28:53.190 --> 28:54.851
Now, within this think tank,

28:54.900 --> 28:56.822
there is a small,
but growing school of thought

28:56.860 --> 28:58.828
_that holds that
the smgle greatest threat

28:58.870 --> 29:00.189
to the human race...

29:00.230 --> 29:02.232
is artificial intelligence.

29:02.270 --> 29:05.034
So, Mason's rant
the other night?

29:05.070 --> 29:06.435
Not as barmy as it sounded.

29:06.470 --> 29:10.338
According to these people,
the very first time

29:10.380 --> 29:13.349
a genuine piece of artificial
intelligence manifests,

29:13.380 --> 29:17.476
we'll be in a fight
for our survival within days.

29:17.520 --> 29:20.512
Now, imagine their quandary.

29:20.550 --> 29:22.450
They have pinpointed
a credible threat,

29:22.490 --> 29:26.085
but it sounds outlandish.

29:26.130 --> 29:27.529
The climate-change people,

29:27.560 --> 29:29.391
they can point
to disastrous examples.

29:29.430 --> 29:31.523
The bio-weapons alarmists,

29:31.570 --> 29:33.561
they have a compelling
narrative to weave.

29:33.600 --> 29:36.239
Even the giant comet people
sound more serious

29:36.270 --> 29:38.329
than the enemies of AI.

29:40.140 --> 29:41.903
So...

29:41.940 --> 29:44.306
these are the people at ETRA
who think AI is a threat?

29:44.350 --> 29:46.102
You think one of them
killed Edwin Borstein,

29:46.150 --> 29:48.141
one of the top engineers
in the field,

29:48.180 --> 29:49.818
and made it look
like Bella did it,

29:49.850 --> 29:52.910
all so they could draw
attention to their cause?

29:52.950 --> 29:54.281
A small-scale incident,

29:54.320 --> 29:56.208
something to get
the media chattering.

29:58.330 --> 30:00.150
Feel free if you'd like
to take a moment

30:00.190 --> 30:01.589
to admire the beauty
of this theory.

30:01.630 --> 30:03.450
'Cause I've done so
several times already myself.

30:03.500 --> 30:05.525
It's elaborate.

30:05.570 --> 30:08.459
But as a motive,
it makes sense.

30:08.500 --> 30:10.934
One of these people
intercepted the package

30:10.970 --> 30:12.267
from Michael Webb
to Edwin Borstein,

30:12.310 --> 30:14.175
and replaced the disk within it.

30:14.210 --> 30:16.201
I've dispatched Kitty
to Webb's apartment

30:16.240 --> 30:18.049
to see if she can_
establish a connection

30:18.080 --> 30:19.945
between him
and one of our suspects.

30:19.980 --> 30:21.516
In the meantime...

30:21.550 --> 30:24.212
we wait.

30:31.330 --> 30:32.319
You said you didn't
set Andrew up

30:32.360 --> 30:33.327
with your friend from Denmark.

30:33.360 --> 30:34.622
I want to believe you.

30:34.660 --> 30:36.525
Well, I encourage you
to do just that then.

30:36.560 --> 30:38.562
I want to believe you,

30:38.600 --> 30:40.329
because if you did do it,
if you still don't

30:40.370 --> 30:42.133
respect the fact
that I need my own space,

30:42.170 --> 30:44.035
then I don't know why
we're trying this again.

30:44.070 --> 30:45.606
(sighs)

30:45.640 --> 30:48.370
Watson, I have no inclination

30:48.410 --> 30:49.604
to excise Andrew from your life.

30:49.640 --> 30:50.868
Why would I?

30:50.910 --> 30:51.979
I like the man.

30:52.010 --> 30:54.376
Oh, you like him?
Yeah.

30:54.420 --> 30:55.512
You-you never told me that.

30:55.550 --> 30:57.541
(stammering):
Why would I tell you?

30:59.020 --> 31:00.510
(stammers, grunts)

31:00.550 --> 31:02.211
To reassure that you've made
a sound choice.

31:02.260 --> 31:04.387
As one might reasonably
expect a friend to do.

31:06.090 --> 31:07.455
Right, right, oh, very well.

31:07.490 --> 31:08.559
I like him.

31:08.600 --> 31:10.295
He's intelligent.

31:10.330 --> 31:11.524
He hasn't just jumped
into a new business.

31:11.570 --> 31:12.992
He has the patience
and self-possession

31:13.030 --> 31:14.463
to wait for
something worthwhile.

31:14.500 --> 31:16.263
And, most importantly,
he understands you.

31:16.300 --> 31:18.461
He understands you and me.

31:18.510 --> 31:19.602
Wh-What do you mean by that?

31:19.640 --> 31:21.505
I mean, Watson,
that whether you care

31:21.540 --> 31:23.508
to admit it lately or not,

31:23.540 --> 31:25.644
I am an important
part of your life.

31:25.680 --> 31:27.648
And, whether I say it
out loud or not,

31:27.680 --> 31:30.513
you are an important
part of mine.

31:30.550 --> 31:32.518
My return to New York

31:32.550 --> 31:33.949
was driven, in large part,

31:33.990 --> 31:36.015
by desire to repair
our relationship.

31:36.060 --> 31:39.325
And I think, even though
we might draw further or nearer

31:39.360 --> 31:41.658
from each other
depending on Circumstance,

31:41.700 --> 31:45.227
you and I are bound...
somehow.

31:46.600 --> 31:48.488
Andrew accepts that

31:48.540 --> 31:50.360
without feeling
needlessly threatened.

31:50.400 --> 31:52.300
_ It's a rather_ _
enlightened p05ition.

31:52.340 --> 31:54.570
And so, no, I've got no desire

31:54.610 --> 31:58.671
to banish the man
to Scandi-bloody-navia.

32:04.050 --> 32:05.540
Okay, I believe you.

32:07.550 --> 32:09.359
Kind of feel like
hugging you right now.

32:09.390 --> 32:11.551
Yet, as my friend,

32:11.590 --> 32:13.581
you know that would be
a rash decision.

32:13.630 --> 32:15.097
(cell phone chimes)

32:18.630 --> 32:20.518
It's Kitty.

32:20.570 --> 32:22.367
She says there's
no connection she can find

32:22.400 --> 32:24.368
between Michael Webb
and one of our suspects.

32:24.410 --> 32:26.970
In fact, she says
his apartment is spotless.

32:27.010 --> 32:29.137
Michael Webb strike you
as the kind of man

32:29.180 --> 32:30.704
to live in a pristine apartment?

32:30.740 --> 32:32.401
No.

32:32.450 --> 32:33.576
Seems like someone
who'd be living

32:33.610 --> 32:35.612
in the middle of a biohazard.

32:35.650 --> 32:38.448
Yeah, I-I got an e-mail from a
place called Clean This House.

32:38.490 --> 32:41.459
They told me that a friend of
mine entered me into a contest,

32:41.490 --> 32:44.220
and I won a package
of free cleanings.

32:44.260 --> 32:45.750
Did you ever think to verify

32:45.790 --> 32:47.587
that Clean This House
was a real company?

32:47.630 --> 32:49.052
Because they don't
have a Web site.

32:49.100 --> 32:50.749
It's a little

32:50.800 --> 32:53.997
suspicious in this day
and age, don't you think?

32:54.040 --> 32:56.235
WATSON: We think the person
who killed Borstein

32:56.270 --> 32:57.999
got into your place
by telling you

32:58.040 --> 32:59.632
you won free cleaning services.

32:59.670 --> 33:01.706
Then they swapped the disc
that you made for him

33:01.740 --> 33:04.072
with one of their own.

33:04.110 --> 33:06.305
So, do you recognize
any of these people?

33:06.350 --> 33:09.478
Ah, well, these people
are all old.

33:09.520 --> 33:11.249
The girl who cleaned my place
was my age.

33:11.290 --> 33:14.259
Are you sure no one looks
familiar to you here?

33:18.460 --> 33:19.722
Uh... hold up.

33:22.600 --> 33:24.090
Her.

33:24.130 --> 33:25.097
Yeah, that's her.

33:25.130 --> 33:26.119
I'm positive.

33:28.570 --> 33:31.733
HOLMES: Isaac Pike is a
professor of computer science.

33:31.770 --> 33:32.600
He's also a vocal alarmist

33:32.640 --> 33:35.279
when it_ comes to
artifICIal intelligence.

33:35.310 --> 33:36.629
Pike was born with
spina bifida.

33:36.680 --> 33:39.171
Been confined to a wheelchair
his entire life.

33:39.210 --> 33:41.610
For obvious reasons, he could
not have executed the plan

33:41.650 --> 33:43.777
to pose as a maid,
but his student...

33:43.820 --> 33:46.084
Erin Rabin...

33:46.120 --> 33:48.179
She's a graduate student
in philosophy.

33:48.220 --> 33:50.359
She took Pike's "Ethics of
Technology" course last semester

33:50.390 --> 33:51.823
and has been assisting
him with his research.

33:51.860 --> 33:53.657
She, no doubt, finds
his ideas compelling.

33:53.690 --> 33:55.692
Well, how do you know she was
doing it for him?

33:55.730 --> 33:56.822
She could've been
working on her own.

33:56.860 --> 33:58.293
She's a philosophy student.

33:58.330 --> 33:59.695
She has no programming
experience.

33:59.730 --> 34:01.436
The virus that
killed Borstein

34:01.470 --> 34:04.268
is a cutting-edge
piece of software.

34:04.310 --> 34:05.208
We can place her
in Webb's apartment

34:05.240 --> 34:06.730
under false pretenses.

34:06.770 --> 34:08.670
That, combined with the
proven existence of the virus,

34:08.710 --> 34:11.440
should be enough to
get a friendly judge
to give us a warrant.

34:11.480 --> 34:14.040
(bell tolling)

34:18.320 --> 34:20.788
Isaac Pike, Erin Rabin,

34:20.820 --> 34:22.219
glad I caught you together.

34:22.260 --> 34:23.488
Detective Marcus Bell, NYPD.

34:23.520 --> 34:25.784
I wonder if you'd
mind coming with me.

34:25.830 --> 34:27.457
I have some questions for you

34:27.490 --> 34:28.821
about the murder
of Edwin Borstein.

34:28.860 --> 34:30.623
Who's Edwin Borstein?

34:30.660 --> 34:32.662
The man you mailed
a computer virus

34:32.700 --> 34:34.338
written by Isaac Pike to.

34:34.370 --> 34:35.735
Sound familiar?

34:37.740 --> 34:40.709
Isaac didn't write the virus.

34:40.740 --> 34:41.809
I did.

34:43.540 --> 34:46.703
I did everything.

34:46.750 --> 34:48.274
It was all my idea.

34:53.920 --> 34:55.683
You have the right
to remain silent,

34:55.720 --> 34:57.153
and refuse_ to
answer questions...

34:57.190 --> 34:58.384
We knew she might crack
under questioning,

34:58.430 --> 34:59.852
but did you think
it'd be this easy?

34:59.890 --> 35:01.152
I don't think catching
both murderers

35:01.200 --> 35:02.690
is going to be
easy at all.

35:02.730 --> 35:04.766
She's lying to us.

35:04.800 --> 35:07.189
She intends to cover up
for her mentor.

35:12.640 --> 35:15.279
I picked Edwin Borstein
as a target.

35:15.310 --> 35:18.575
I went to the same Web sites
he did,

35:18.610 --> 35:21.545
figured out who
he was corresponding with,

35:21.580 --> 35:23.810
and then I wrote the virus,

35:23.850 --> 35:27.411
posed as a maid,
and had it mailed to Borstein.

35:27.450 --> 35:29.486
BELL: You have zero
programming experience

35:29.520 --> 35:31.522
whatsoever.

35:31.560 --> 35:34.529
You really asking me to believe
that you taught yourself

35:34.560 --> 35:36.289
to write a computer virus
that eats itself?

35:36.330 --> 35:39.720
IfI give you a piece
of paper right now...

35:40.630 --> 35:42.530
...could you write a little
program for us?

35:47.710 --> 35:50.235
PIKE: Erin was
a conscientious student.

35:50.280 --> 35:52.578
I know she took my work
very seriously.

35:52.610 --> 35:56.216
But I would never
advocate harming somebody.

35:56.250 --> 35:58.912
We're executing a search warrant
on your computer, as we speak.

35:58.950 --> 36:02.215
If there's any trace
of that virus on there,

36:02.260 --> 36:03.579
we'll find it.

36:03.620 --> 36:05.656
BELL: _ _
Why are you making this

36:05.690 --> 36:07.328
so easy for us?

36:07.360 --> 36:08.622
Because I don't want you

36:08.660 --> 36:10.651
dragging Isaac's name
through the mud.

36:10.700 --> 36:12.520
His work is
too important.

36:12.570 --> 36:16.199
None of us can afford
for it to be interrupted.

36:17.440 --> 36:19.567
So she's covering for him.

36:19.610 --> 36:21.703
GREGSON: There's not much
I can do-- she confessed.

36:21.740 --> 36:24.470
There's nothing tying Pike
to the murder, other than you

36:24.510 --> 36:25.977
saying Erin Rabin couldn't
have written that virus.

36:26.010 --> 36:27.978
Could we hold him overnight?

36:28.010 --> 36:29.546
Maybe if we had
a little more time...

36:29.580 --> 36:31.616
GREGSON: The search warrant
turned up nothing.

36:31.650 --> 36:33.686
Erin confessed.

36:33.720 --> 36:35.654
Unless something changes,
the story she told us

36:35.690 --> 36:37.681
is gonna be
the official version

36:37.720 --> 36:39.722
of Edwin Borstein's murder.

36:46.730 --> 36:48.595
(violin music playing
over stereo)

36:48.640 --> 36:50.437
(cell phone ringing)

36:52.040 --> 36:53.598
(sighs)

36:56.680 --> 36:58.944
(home phone ringing)

37:06.650 --> 37:08.254
That was Joan.

37:08.290 --> 37:09.780
She knows you won't come
to the phone when you're...

37:09.820 --> 37:11.651
like this.

37:11.690 --> 37:13.351
She wants to come round
and help.

37:13.390 --> 37:14.891
That won't be necessary.

37:14.930 --> 37:19.663
At times, Watson presents
certain... moral guidelines,

37:19.700 --> 37:21.759
and they can be
an impediment to progress.

37:23.670 --> 37:25.661
We're going to spend
the rest of the evening

37:25.710 --> 37:27.701
looking at the friends
and family of Isaac Pike.

37:28.940 --> 37:30.476
Why?

37:30.510 --> 37:32.899
Erin Rabin is willing to spend
her life in prison

37:32.950 --> 37:35.373
if it means_ that Pike_is free
to continue working.

37:35.420 --> 37:37.274
She's has made it all but
impossible for us

37:37.320 --> 37:39.538
to prove that
he is behind the killing.

37:39.590 --> 37:42.753
So we are going to have to
settle for the next best thing:

37:42.790 --> 37:46.749
getting him to admit
that he did it.

37:50.900 --> 37:52.390
Isaac Pike.

37:52.430 --> 37:53.727
Sherlock Holmes.

37:53.770 --> 37:55.362
We met briefly at the police
station last night.

37:55.400 --> 37:57.698
Mr. Holmes.

37:57.740 --> 37:59.867
Do I need a lawyer?

37:59.910 --> 38:01.730
No, you won't want her
here for this.

38:01.780 --> 38:03.975
You see, you and I both know
that you are the mind

38:04.010 --> 38:05.841
behind the murder
of Edwin Borstein,

38:05.880 --> 38:08.713
just as we both know that, as
long as your student holds fast

38:08.750 --> 38:11.742
to her story, I will never
be able to prove your guilt.

38:11.790 --> 38:12.939
That's a problem.

38:12.990 --> 38:15.015
But not an insurmountable one.

38:15.060 --> 38:17.312
You have
a younger brother-- Joshua.

38:17.360 --> 38:18.952
He hasn't quite reached
the heights that you have.

38:18.990 --> 38:20.787
In fact, he's had some
struggles, hasn't he?

38:20.830 --> 38:22.024
Drugs, alcohol...

38:22.060 --> 38:23.823
What's your point?

38:23.860 --> 38:26.021
He's been convicted of
two drug-related felonies.

38:26.070 --> 38:28.630
And since he's made the mistake
of living in Jersey City,

38:28.670 --> 38:29.898
one more conviction makes him

38:29.940 --> 38:30.895
eligible for a sentence
of 25 years to life

38:30.940 --> 38:32.805
under the state's horrific
three strikes law.

38:32.840 --> 38:34.876
My associate took
some photographs of him

38:34.910 --> 38:37.970
buying a rather large
amount of heroin,
just this morning.

38:43.380 --> 38:44.938
(quietly):
Oh...

38:46.990 --> 38:48.651
(wry laugh)

38:48.690 --> 38:51.989
You want me to confess...

38:52.030 --> 38:53.952
and, if I do,
you'll-you'll-you'll

38:53.990 --> 38:57.096
get rid of this folder
full of blackmail.

38:57.130 --> 38:59.121
I imagine you care quite deeply
about your brother,

38:59.170 --> 39:00.990
or you wouldn't have paid
his way through rehab

39:01.030 --> 39:02.691
half a dozen times already.

39:02.740 --> 39:04.367
Take two hours
to think it over,

39:04.410 --> 39:06.503
and if I haven't
heard from you...

39:06.540 --> 39:09.668
I did a little research
of my own last night.

39:09.710 --> 39:10.972
I was curious why
the NYPD

39:11.010 --> 39:12.671
had a consultant.

39:12.710 --> 39:14.610
You've got
a very impressive record--

39:14.650 --> 39:17.016
prolific, too-- except for
a couple of years ago,

39:17.050 --> 39:18.711
when you suddenly disappeared
for six months.

39:18.750 --> 39:20.911
Six months--
that's the length

39:20.950 --> 39:24.989
of a very serious
in-patient rehab.

39:25.030 --> 39:27.783
A man of your unique
sensitivities--

39:27.830 --> 39:29.889
I'm sure it's tempting to dull

39:29.930 --> 39:31.898
those senses.

39:31.930 --> 39:34.069
My history has little to do
with the matter at hand.

39:34.100 --> 39:36.034
I think it may.

39:36.070 --> 39:39.039
I think it unlikely that
a recovering addict

39:39.070 --> 39:42.437
would send another_troubled soul
to rot in prison,

39:42.480 --> 39:45.745
just to have the satisfaction
of putting away his man.

39:45.780 --> 39:49.409
That would require
ruthlessness,

39:49.450 --> 39:52.089
a kind of... machine logic...

39:52.120 --> 39:53.189
mm...

39:53.220 --> 39:55.711
I'm not sure you have.

39:55.760 --> 39:57.955
Not entirely, anyway.

39:57.990 --> 39:59.924
Same kind of
machine logic you used

39:59.960 --> 40:01.086
when you murdered
Edwin Borstein.

40:01.130 --> 40:02.597
Some math equations

40:02.630 --> 40:05.667
are more compelling than others.

40:05.700 --> 40:08.965
Yours is a one-to-one exchange:
my brother for me.

40:09.000 --> 40:11.560
The equation you attribute to me

40:11.610 --> 40:14.670
trades one man's life

40:14.710 --> 40:17.577
for the chance to prevent
billions of deaths.

40:17.610 --> 40:20.204
You're talking about
nothing less than

40:20.250 --> 40:22.115
the survival of the species.

40:22.150 --> 40:26.689
Surely that's worth compromising
one's values for?

40:27.820 --> 40:29.117
In any case...

40:29.160 --> 40:32.755
I think you're bluffing.

40:32.790 --> 40:34.121
You might want the world
to believe

40:34.160 --> 40:36.458
that you're an automaton,

40:36.500 --> 40:39.060
a calculating machine...

40:39.100 --> 40:42.695
but you and I know better.

40:42.740 --> 40:46.005
Or we will, anyway...

40:46.040 --> 40:48.031
in a couple of hours.

40:56.150 --> 40:58.983
(footsteps descending stairs)

40:59.020 --> 41:01.659
KITTY:
Hey...

41:01.690 --> 41:03.112
I didn't see anything
on the news

41:03.160 --> 41:04.115
about Pike getting arrested.

41:04.160 --> 41:05.525
Nothing about his brother

41:05.560 --> 41:06.959
on the police band, either.

41:06.990 --> 41:09.220
What happened?

41:10.300 --> 41:12.518
He wouldn't confess.

41:12.570 --> 41:14.868
And you couldn't
turn in his brother.

41:14.900 --> 41:17.164
We can still
keep looking for a way

41:17.200 --> 41:19.168
to prove that Pike did it.

41:19.210 --> 41:21.030
The Property Clerk's
Office called.

41:21.070 --> 41:23.573
They want to know when they can
come and pick up Bella.

41:23.610 --> 41:26.170
I need a couple
more hours with her.

41:26.210 --> 41:28.610
Thank you.

